This script adapts the QtWebKit parser for Ruby 3.x instead of 2.x, the old code assumes that
tokens are strings, while newer Ruby is giving structured objects. The patch adds another condition
to handle the Annotations properly.
Without this, the build creaks with the following:
undefined method '=~' for an instance of Annotation (NoMethodError)

Author: Stamen Miroslavov <stamen.miroslavov@bsc.es>
Barcelona Supercomputing Center 2026
diff -ruNBbw a/Source/JavaScriptCore/offlineasm/parser.rb b/Source/JavaScriptCore/offlineasm/parser.rb
--- a/Source/JavaScriptCore/offlineasm/parser.rb	2020-03-10 03:14:41.000000000 +0100
+++ b/Source/JavaScriptCore/offlineasm/parser.rb	2026-03-25 16:11:23.767976803 +0100
@@ -584,9 +584,7 @@
         firstCodeOrigin = @tokens[@idx].codeOrigin
         list = []
         loop {
-            if (@idx == @tokens.length and not final) or (final and @tokens[@idx] =~ final)
-                break
-            elsif @tokens[@idx].is_a? Annotation
+            if @tokens[@idx].is_a? Annotation
                 # This is the only place where we can encounter a global
                 # annotation, and hence need to be able to distinguish between
                 # them.
@@ -600,6 +598,8 @@
                 list << Instruction.new(codeOrigin, annotationOpcode, [], @tokens[@idx].string)
                 @annotation = nil
                 @idx += 2 # Consume the newline as well.
+            elsif (@idx == @tokens.length and not final) or (final and @tokens[@idx] =~ final)
+                break
             elsif @tokens[@idx] == "\n"
                 # ignore
                 @idx += 1
